1. Package Managers

DPKG/APT - Debian based system
RPM - for Redhat and centos

2. One of the to differentiate different distributions of linux is through package manager

- distributions like redhat,centos and fedora are based on rpm package manager and hence they are known as RPM based distributions

- The debian family including ubuntu,Debian,Arch Linux ,Linux Mint etc make use of debian package managers such as DPKG

3. What is a package ?
- A package , in its simplest definition is a compressed archive that contains all the files that are required by our particular software to run.

e.g lets install GIMP(an image editing software which stands for GNU Image Manipulation Program).

To do this can make use of gimp.deb package. This gimp.deb package contains all the software binaries and files needed for image editor to run along with metadata , which provides information about the software itself.

4. A package manager is a software in a Linux system that provides a consistent and automated process of installing, upgrading and configuring and removing packages from the operating system. 

5. Functions of package manager 
- Package integrity and Authenticity

 • Some of the essential functions of a package manager are ensuring the integrity and authenticity of the package by verifying their digital certificates and checksums.This is to ensure that the package is downloaded from a trusted source and safe to install.

- Simplified Package Management

• Simplifying the entire package management process. Most package managers provide powerful querying options making it easier to lookup packages and then downloading , installing or updating existing software from a software repository.

- Grouping packages by function to reduce user confusion

- Manage dependencies to ensure a package is installed with all packages it requires, this avoiding what is commonly called as dependency hell.

6. Different types of package managers 
- DPKG - package manager for debian based distributions
- APT - a newer front end for the dpkg system found in debian based distributions
- APT-GET - traditional front end for dpkg system
- RPM - base package manager found in redhat based distributions
- YUM - a front end for RPM system found in redhat based distributions
- DNF - a more feature rich front end for RPM system found in redhat based distributions
